.SS "\fBDECLSPEC\fP \fBUint32\fP \fBSDLCALL\fP SDL_GetQueuedAudioSize (\fBSDL_AudioDeviceID\fP dev)"
Get the number of bytes of still-queued audio\&.
.PP
For playback devices: this is the number of bytes that have been queued for playback with \fBSDL_QueueAudio()\fP, but have not yet been sent to the hardware\&.
.PP
Once we've sent it to the hardware, this function can not decide the exact byte boundary of what has been played\&. It's possible that we just gave the hardware several kilobytes right before you called this function, but it hasn't played any of it yet, or maybe half of it, etc\&.
.PP
For capture devices, this is the number of bytes that have been captured by the device and are waiting for you to dequeue\&. This number may grow at any time, so this only informs of the lower-bound of available data\&.
.PP
You may not queue or dequeue audio on a device that is using an application-supplied callback; calling this function on such a device always returns 0\&. You have to use the audio callback or queue audio, but not both\&.
.PP
You should not call \fBSDL_LockAudio()\fP on the device before querying; SDL handles locking internally for this function\&.
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fIdev\fP the device ID of which we will query queued audio size 
.RE
.PP
\fBReturns\fP
.RS 4
the number of bytes (not samples!) of queued audio\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBSince\fP
.RS 4
This function is available since SDL 2\&.0\&.4\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBSDL_ClearQueuedAudio\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_QueueAudio\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_DequeueAudio\fP 
.RE
.PP

.SS "\fBDECLSPEC\fP \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP *\fBSDLCALL\fP SDL_LoadWAV_RW (\fBSDL_RWops\fP * src, int freesrc, \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP * spec, \fBUint8\fP ** audio_buf, \fBUint32\fP * audio_len)"
Load the audio data of a WAVE file into memory\&.
.PP
Loading a WAVE file requires \fCsrc\fP, \fCspec\fP, \fCaudio_buf\fP and \fCaudio_len\fP to be valid pointers\&. The entire data portion of the file is then loaded into memory and decoded if necessary\&.
.PP
If \fCfreesrc\fP is non-zero, the data source gets automatically closed and freed before the function returns\&.
.PP
Supported formats are RIFF WAVE files with the formats PCM (8, 16, 24, and 32 bits), IEEE Float (32 bits), Microsoft ADPCM and IMA ADPCM (4 bits), and A-law and mu-law (8 bits)\&. Other formats are currently unsupported and cause an error\&.
.PP
If this function succeeds, the pointer returned by it is equal to \fCspec\fP and the pointer to the audio data allocated by the function is written to \fCaudio_buf\fP and its length in bytes to \fCaudio_len\fP\&. The \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP members \fCfreq\fP, \fCchannels\fP, and \fCformat\fP are set to the values of the audio data in the buffer\&. The \fCsamples\fP member is set to a sane default and all others are set to zero\&.
.PP
It's necessary to use \fBSDL_FreeWAV()\fP to free the audio data returned in \fCaudio_buf\fP when it is no longer used\&.
.PP
Because of the underspecification of the \&.WAV format, there are many problematic files in the wild that cause issues with strict decoders\&. To provide compatibility with these files, this decoder is lenient in regards to the truncation of the file, the fact chunk, and the size of the RIFF chunk\&. The hints \fCSDL_HINT_WAVE_RIFF_CHUNK_SIZE\fP, \fCSDL_HINT_WAVE_TRUNCATION\fP, and \fCSDL_HINT_WAVE_FACT_CHUNK\fP can be used to tune the behavior of the loading process\&.
.PP
Any file that is invalid (due to truncation, corruption, or wrong values in the headers), too big, or unsupported causes an error\&. Additionally, any critical I/O error from the data source will terminate the loading process with an error\&. The function returns NULL on error and in all cases (with the exception of \fCsrc\fP being NULL), an appropriate error message will be set\&.
.PP
It is required that the data source supports seeking\&.
.PP
Example:
.PP
.PP
.nf
SDL_LoadWAV_RW(SDL_RWFromFile("sample\&.wav", "rb"), 1, &spec, &buf, &len);
.fi
.PP
.PP
Note that the SDL_LoadWAV macro does this same thing for you, but in a less messy way:
.PP
.PP
.nf
SDL_LoadWAV("sample\&.wav", &spec, &buf, &len);
.fi
.PP
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fIsrc\fP The data source for the WAVE data 
.br
\fIfreesrc\fP If non-zero, SDL will \fIalways\fP free the data source 
.br
\fIspec\fP An \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP that will be filled in with the wave file's format details 
.br
\fIaudio_buf\fP A pointer filled with the audio data, allocated by the function\&. 
.br
\fIaudio_len\fP A pointer filled with the length of the audio data buffer in bytes 
.RE
.PP
\fBReturns\fP
.RS 4
This function, if successfully called, returns \fCspec\fP, which will be filled with the audio data format of the wave source data\&. \fCaudio_buf\fP will be filled with a pointer to an allocated buffer containing the audio data, and \fCaudio_len\fP is filled with the length of that audio buffer in bytes\&.
.RE
.PP
This function returns NULL if the \&.WAV file cannot be opened, uses an unknown data format, or is corrupt; call \fBSDL_GetError()\fP for more information\&.
.PP
When the application is done with the data returned in \fCaudio_buf\fP, it should call \fBSDL_FreeWAV()\fP to dispose of it\&.
.PP
\fBSince\fP
.RS 4
This function is available since SDL 2\&.0\&.0\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBSDL_FreeWAV\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_LoadWAV\fP 
.RE
.PP

