.SS "\fBDECLSPEC\fP \fBvoid\fP \fBSDLCALL\fP SDL_MixAudioFormat (\fBUint8\fP * dst, const \fBUint8\fP * src, \fBSDL_AudioFormat\fP format, \fBUint32\fP len, int volume)"
Mix audio data in a specified format\&.
.PP
This takes an audio buffer \fCsrc\fP of \fClen\fP bytes of \fCformat\fP data and mixes it into \fCdst\fP, performing addition, volume adjustment, and overflow clipping\&. The buffer pointed to by \fCdst\fP must also be \fClen\fP bytes of \fCformat\fP data\&.
.PP
This is provided for convenience -- you can mix your own audio data\&.
.PP
Do not use this function for mixing together more than two streams of sample data\&. The output from repeated application of this function may be distorted by clipping, because there is no accumulator with greater range than the input (not to mention this being an inefficient way of doing it)\&.
.PP
It is a common misconception that this function is required to write audio data to an output stream in an audio callback\&. While you can do that, \fBSDL_MixAudioFormat()\fP is really only needed when you're mixing a single audio stream with a volume adjustment\&.
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
