.SS "\fBDECLSPEC\fP int \fBSDLCALL\fP SDL_OpenAudio (\fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP * desired, \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP * obtained)"
This function is a legacy means of opening the audio device\&.
.PP
This function remains for compatibility with SDL 1\&.2, but also because it's slightly easier to use than the new functions in SDL 2\&.0\&. The new, more powerful, and preferred way to do this is \fBSDL_OpenAudioDevice()\fP\&.
.PP
This function is roughly equivalent to:
.PP
.PP
.nf
SDL_OpenAudioDevice(NULL, 0, desired, obtained, SDL_AUDIO_ALLOW_ANY_CHANGE);
.fi
.PP
.PP
With two notable exceptions:
.PP
.IP "\(bu" 2
If \fCobtained\fP is NULL, we use \fCdesired\fP (and allow no changes), which means desired will be modified to have the correct values for silence, etc, and SDL will convert any differences between your app's specific request and the hardware behind the scenes\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
The return value is always success or failure, and not a device ID, which means you can only have one device open at a time with this function\&.
.PP
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fIdesired\fP an \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP structure representing the desired output format\&. Please refer to the SDL_OpenAudioDevice documentation for details on how to prepare this structure\&. 
.br
\fIobtained\fP an \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP structure filled in with the actual parameters, or NULL\&. 
.RE
.PP
\fBReturns\fP
.RS 4
0 if successful, placing the actual hardware parameters in the structure pointed to by \fCobtained\fP\&.
.RE
.PP
If \fCobtained\fP is NULL, the audio data passed to the callback function will be guaranteed to be in the requested format, and will be automatically converted to the actual hardware audio format if necessary\&. If \fCobtained\fP is NULL, \fCdesired\fP will have fields modified\&.
.PP
This function returns a negative error code on failure to open the audio device or failure to set up the audio thread; call \fBSDL_GetError()\fP for more information\&.
.PP
\fBSince\fP
.RS 4
This function is available since SDL 2\&.0\&.0\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBSDL_CloseAudio\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_LockAudio\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_PauseAudio\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_UnlockAudio\fP 
.RE
.PP

.SS "\fBDECLSPEC\fP \fBSDL_AudioDeviceID\fP \fBSDLCALL\fP SDL_OpenAudioDevice (const char * device, int iscapture, const \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP * desired, \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP * obtained, int allowed_changes)"
Open a specific audio device\&.
.PP
\fBSDL_OpenAudio()\fP, unlike this function, always acts on device ID 1\&. As such, this function will never return a 1 so as not to conflict with the legacy function\&.
.PP
Please note that SDL 2\&.0 before 2\&.0\&.5 did not support recording; as such, this function would fail if \fCiscapture\fP was not zero\&. Starting with SDL 2\&.0\&.5, recording is implemented and this value can be non-zero\&.
.PP
Passing in a \fCdevice\fP name of NULL requests the most reasonable default (and is equivalent to what \fBSDL_OpenAudio()\fP does to choose a device)\&. The \fCdevice\fP name is a UTF-8 string reported by \fBSDL_GetAudioDeviceName()\fP, but some drivers allow arbitrary and driver-specific strings, such as a hostname/IP address for a remote audio server, or a filename in the diskaudio driver\&.
.PP
An opened audio device starts out paused, and should be enabled for playing by calling SDL_PauseAudioDevice(devid, 0) when you are ready for your audio callback function to be called\&. Since the audio driver may modify the requested size of the audio buffer, you should allocate any local mixing buffers after you open the audio device\&.
.PP
The audio callback runs in a separate thread in most cases; you can prevent race conditions between your callback and other threads without fully pausing playback with \fBSDL_LockAudioDevice()\fP\&. For more information about the callback, see \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP\&.
.PP
Managing the audio spec via 'desired' and 'obtained':
.PP
When filling in the desired audio spec structure:
.PP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCdesired->freq\fP should be the frequency in sample-frames-per-second (Hz)\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCdesired->format\fP should be the audio format (\fCAUDIO_S16SYS\fP, etc)\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCdesired->samples\fP is the desired size of the audio buffer, in \fIsample frames\fP (with stereo output, two samples--left and right--would make a single sample frame)\&. This number should be a power of two, and may be adjusted by the audio driver to a value more suitable for the hardware\&. Good values seem to range between 512 and 8096 inclusive, depending on the application and CPU speed\&. Smaller values reduce latency, but can lead to underflow if the application is doing heavy processing and cannot fill the audio buffer in time\&. Note that the number of sample frames is directly related to time by the following formula: \fCms = (sampleframes*1000)/freq\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCdesired->size\fP is the size in \fIbytes\fP of the audio buffer, and is calculated by \fBSDL_OpenAudioDevice()\fP\&. You don't initialize this\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCdesired->silence\fP is the value used to set the buffer to silence, and is calculated by \fBSDL_OpenAudioDevice()\fP\&. You don't initialize this\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCdesired->callback\fP should be set to a function that will be called when the audio device is ready for more data\&. It is passed a pointer to the audio buffer, and the length in bytes of the audio buffer\&. This function usually runs in a separate thread, and so you should protect data structures that it accesses by calling \fBSDL_LockAudioDevice()\fP and \fBSDL_UnlockAudioDevice()\fP in your code\&. Alternately, you may pass a NULL pointer here, and call \fBSDL_QueueAudio()\fP with some frequency, to queue more audio samples to be played (or for capture devices, call \fBSDL_DequeueAudio()\fP with some frequency, to obtain audio samples)\&.
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCdesired->userdata\fP is passed as the first parameter to your callback function\&. If you passed a NULL callback, this value is ignored\&.
.PP
.PP
\fCallowed_changes\fP can have the following flags OR'd together:
.PP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCSDL_AUDIO_ALLOW_FREQUENCY_CHANGE\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCSDL_AUDIO_ALLOW_FORMAT_CHANGE\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCSDL_AUDIO_ALLOW_CHANNELS_CHANGE\fP
.IP "\(bu" 2
\fCSDL_AUDIO_ALLOW_ANY_CHANGE\fP
.PP
.PP
These flags specify how SDL should behave when a device cannot offer a specific feature\&. If the application requests a feature that the hardware doesn't offer, SDL will always try to get the closest equivalent\&.
.PP
For example, if you ask for float32 audio format, but the sound card only supports int16, SDL will set the hardware to int16\&. If you had set SDL_AUDIO_ALLOW_FORMAT_CHANGE, SDL will change the format in the \fCobtained\fP structure\&. If that flag was \fInot\fP set, SDL will prepare to convert your callback's float32 audio to int16 before feeding it to the hardware and will keep the originally requested format in the \fCobtained\fP structure\&.
.PP
The resulting audio specs, varying depending on hardware and on what changes were allowed, will then be written back to \fCobtained\fP\&.
.PP
If your application can only handle one specific data format, pass a zero for \fCallowed_changes\fP and let SDL transparently handle any differences\&.
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fIdevice\fP a UTF-8 string reported by \fBSDL_GetAudioDeviceName()\fP or a driver-specific name as appropriate\&. NULL requests the most reasonable default device\&. 
.br
\fIiscapture\fP non-zero to specify a device should be opened for recording, not playback 
.br
\fIdesired\fP an \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP structure representing the desired output format; see \fBSDL_OpenAudio()\fP for more information 
.br
\fIobtained\fP an \fBSDL_AudioSpec\fP structure filled in with the actual output format; see \fBSDL_OpenAudio()\fP for more information 
.br
\fIallowed_changes\fP 0, or one or more flags OR'd together 
.RE
.PP
\fBReturns\fP
.RS 4
a valid device ID that is > 0 on success or 0 on failure; call \fBSDL_GetError()\fP for more information\&.
.RE
.PP
For compatibility with SDL 1\&.2, this will never return 1, since SDL reserves that ID for the legacy \fBSDL_OpenAudio()\fP function\&.
.PP
\fBSince\fP
.RS 4
This function is available since SDL 2\&.0\&.0\&.
.RE
.PP
\fBSee also\fP
.RS 4
\fBSDL_CloseAudioDevice\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_GetAudioDeviceName\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_LockAudioDevice\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_OpenAudio\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_PauseAudioDevice\fP 
.PP
\fBSDL_UnlockAudioDevice\fP 
.RE
.PP

