.SS "\fBDECLSPEC\fP \fBvoid\fP \fBSDLCALL\fP SDL_PauseAudioDevice (\fBSDL_AudioDeviceID\fP dev, int pause_on)"
Use this function to pause and unpause audio playback on a specified device\&.
.PP
This function pauses and unpauses the audio callback processing for a given device\&. Newly-opened audio devices start in the paused state, so you must call this function with \fBpause_on\fP=0 after opening the specified audio device to start playing sound\&. This allows you to safely initialize data for your callback function after opening the audio device\&. Silence will be written to the audio device while paused, and the audio callback is guaranteed to not be called\&. Pausing one device does not prevent other unpaused devices from running their callbacks\&.
.PP
Pausing state does not stack; even if you pause a device several times, a single unpause will start the device playing again, and vice versa\&. This is different from how \fBSDL_LockAudioDevice()\fP works\&.
.PP
If you just need to protect a few variables from race conditions vs your callback, you shouldn't pause the audio device, as it will lead to dropouts in the audio playback\&. Instead, you should use \fBSDL_LockAudioDevice()\fP\&.
.PP
\fBParameters\fP
.RS 4
\fIdev\fP a device opened by \fBSDL_OpenAudioDevice()\fP 
.br
\fIpause_on\fP non-zero to pause, 0 to unpause
.RE
.PP
